{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_chrysocolla_ver01/data/sn89070012/00517019549/1949041401/1031.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nBrewery Gulch Gazette\n1\n33 Subway Bisbee, Arizona Phone 200\nPublished Every Thursday\nI'. A. McKINNEY, Editor and Publisher\nW. F. SKINFILL, Assistant Business Manager\nNational Advertising Representative\nNEWSPAPER AIIVjERtT^IZVG SERVICE. INC.\n|an affiliate of the Nation* l Editorial Association)\nJ In. a. s.\nServing America's Advertisers and^the Home Town Newspapers\nIM W. Randolph Chicago I.HI OFFICES Holbrook Bldg., San Francitco, Cal\nThis newspaper It a mamber of r\nArizona Newspapers on\nfees Graatar Public s\u2022<*\u2022<\u2022 1\nNATIONAL EDITORIAL\nSubscription $2.50 per year, oy mail. Entered as second-class\nmatter May 22, 1931, at the post office at Bisbee. Arizona, under\nthe act of March 3, 1879.\nCHARLIE CROSS MARRIES\nMEXICAN COUPLE WITH\nDOCTOR BOOK 40 YEARS AGO\n(Continued firm Page One)\nwer yes or no, snakin\u2019 his head\nas to which he wanted. Wall, in\nthe course of half a hour he pro\nnounced them man and wife and\nthey went away and lived happy\never after, so far as we ever\nknew. And I guess Charlie would\nof taken all the \u2019dobes that poor\nkid had es we hadn\u2019t butted in\nand told \u2019em we\u2019d take care of\nthe fee.\n\"Yes sir,\u201d Hank concluded,\n\"Charlie still lives hereabouts\nDouglas I recollect \u2014and es you\never have him ask you to go snipe\nhuntin\u2019 or go shootin\u2019 milormo\nbirds take a tip from me brother\nand decline the invitations.\n\u2019Cause that bird still lays awake\nthinkin\u2019 up tricks-I\u2019ll be damned!\nThat son of a\u2014well now, es he\ndidn\u2019t give me a Confederate bill\nfor that hair cut!\u201d\nRYDING THE RANGE WITH\nJACK VAN RYDER\n(Continued From Page One)\nbeing producers of wealth, they\nhad no other source of livelihood,\nand gave the rest to the king.\nSoon the storehouse was filled\nwith treasure again, and the king\nwas pleased with it saying: \u201cHave\nI not dealt fairly with my peo\nple?\u201d\nSome of the people were\npleased and some were not. The\npoor said: \u201cWhy should we work\nany more? The king will take\ncare of us.\u201d The rich said: \u201cWhy\nshould we work any more when\nthe king takes away from us the\nwealth we produce?\u201d\nAnd so the people worked less\nand less, and every time after\nthat when the tax collectors came\namong them, there was less\nwealth to divide.\nInstead of everybody getting\nmore, everybody got less. But the\ntax collectors were happy, be\ncause they always got their share,\nand the king was happy because\nhis store house was always re\nplenished. \u201cI have given every\nbody a fair deal,\u201d the king said.\nThis is not as fantastic a tale\nas it sounds. As Henry Hazlitt\nwrote in a recent issue of News\nweek, \u201cThe Government cannot\ndistribute more under President\nTruman\u2019s fancy handout program\nthan the people can produce. And\nit is not the Government which\nproduces wealth, but private en\nterprise. But before the Govern\nment can give part of this wealth\nto some of the people, it must\ntake it away from others.\u201d\nCiting the President\u2019s demand\nfor \u201cprompt Federal financial aid\nto the States,\u201d Hazlitt pointed out\nthat the Federal Government has\nnothing it can give to the States\nthat it doesn\u2019t first of all take\nfrom the people of the States.\nThis is true of every instance\nin which the administration pro\nposes to distribute Federal\nlargesse. The money first must be\ntaken from some people before\nit is given to others. Frequently\nit will be taken from the same\npeople who are intended to be\nthe ultimate beneficiaries.\nBut in no case do the people\nget back all that is taken from\nthem. The Federal Government\ngets a rake-off on every pot to\npay the cost of administration\nand, incidentally, to support an\never growing Federal bureauc\nracy.\nSuch financial legerdemain\neventually must lead to a tax\nburden which will devour the re\nwards of prudence, thrift, indus\ntry, skill, and foresight, and de\nstroy the incentives to work and\nproduce. We are farther along the\nroad than we think.\nCongressional Record, Page A\n1523. 81st Congress.)\nCANADA CUTS TAXES\nTO HALT RECESSION\nCanadian Finance Minister\nDouglas Abbott is convinced that\ninflation in the land of the maple\nleaf is a thing of the past, says\nthe Washington, Pa., Observer.\nHe thinks that at least another\nyear of unexcelled prosperity lies\nahead. Therefore, he is passing\nalong some of the benefits of this\nhappy situation to the paying cus\ntomers, the Canadian people.\nCanada is taking realistic ac-\nW OcANNNRVIRUt /Oy siHSrW\nSupsrsiwohW.\nNUMBER 13 IS W\n-WWW BECAUSETHEIS\n\"WWW \"I IS\u00aeWMI-6OD\nI?, i MOULDED 8V LUCK!\neccentric of rye, sr\nEngland, Willed twat his A z\ngravestone be Placed on the 'i\nPoof of his h0me....50 his v\ngLWTWES AND FRIENDS WOULD A\nBE reminded OF him constantly I IKHS\nOF INDIA\nWk I Cj\u00ae TURBANS\na Jk\n-A- LETTER\nWk 4ad rerosed at\n-\u2014-^twe bottom of the sea for i\n184-\u2022 lo TEARS WAS DELIVERED IN OAKLAND. Eh\u00bb\nBREWERY GULCH GAZETTE\nHAVE A HEART\nil:\ntion to head off depression. In\ncome taxes will be reduced by ap\nproximately 32 percent. Taxes on\nthe earnings of small businesses\nwill also be reduced, and import\nrestrictions on a long list of com\nmodities will be relaxed. Taxes\non jewelry will be reduced by\nhalf to 10 percent. Many other\nlevies and luxury taxes will be\nwiped out altogether.\nNot only is a 32-percent reduc\ntion in income taxes something to\ngloat over, but for the first time\nin history taxes in Canada will\nbe lower than in the United\nStates. Income-tax rates on mid\ndle-bracket incomes in Canada\nwill be one-half those in effect in\nthe States.\nCanada\u2019s come-back from the\ngloomy vistas of a tight war econ\nomy has been nothing short of\nphenomenal. It shows good man\nagement and a will to live in the\nsunlight of a free economy. Can\nada has achieved the state which\ncitizens of the United States\nlooked forward to fondly at the\nend of the war\u2014a prosperous era\nwith drastic reduction in wartime\ntaxes.\nSenator George, Democrat, of\nGeorgia, advocates adoption of a\npolicy similar to that ordered in\nCanada by the United States.\nChairman of the Senate Finance\nCommittee, he has long special-\nITSAMAZING!\nBISBEE, ARIZONA, THURSDAY, APRIL 14, 1949\nBy MACKENZIE\nized in public fiscal matters.\nHe referred to the fact that\nCanada is adopting such a policy\neven though that Dominion has a\npublic debt which is comparative\nly greater than that of the Unit\ned States. He made this reference\nin citing that reduction of public\ndebt is one of the reasons ad\nvanced by advocates of higher\ntaxes.\nThere is no good reason why\nthe spending of the United States\nshould not be reduced to make a\npayment on the public debt pos\nsible under even present condi\ntions. Even with all the talk of\nrecession, business activity is still\nat a very high rate. A leveling off\nis inevitable but even so the out\nlook for business for some months\nahead is still good.\nConditions will be somewhat\ndifferent but the need for things\nstill exists and there are many\nwho want them.\nPerhaps Congress should ap\npoint a joint committee to tour\nCanada and learn how it was ac\ncomplished there. Perhaps the\nWhite House should send a rep\nresentative on a similar mission.\nRoscoe Says:\nThe reason why my gal re\nminds me of a switchboard is be\ncause when she walks all her lines\nare busy.\n^^Commentator\ns\nBy Jim Larkin\n\"Hope springs eternal in the human\nbreast\"\nt How true, indeed! I know I shall\nnot rest\nUntil\u2014as oft before\u2014l dig and delve\nt Hours daily; and on week ends,\nmaybe twelve\nThen I'll await my fine truck-garden\ncrop\nWhich, no doubt, once again will\nbe a flop.\nh\nHAJALA\nthe\nT ma d\nsat with us around the fireplace\nas we debated the question: What\nis the principal human failing?\nAsked for an opinion, hq spoke:\nIn the days when Mahomet\ndjvelt among human beings, it\nwas noted that at times a dove\nwas perched upon his shoulder,\nand ever and anon would the dove\nput its bill to Mahomet\u2019s ear.\nWhen watchers asked regarding\nthis, they were told that the dove\nwas\u2019 a holy spirit which whisper\ned into the ear of the Prophet\nthe will of Allah. Then did the\npeople marvel much. They knew\nnot that seeds were placed within\nMahomet\u2019s ear and that, in truth,\nthe dove was only feasting. Still\nmuch neglected today is the full\nuse of our reasoning powers; still\nrare is the application of that\nwhich strangely is misnamed\n\"common\" sense.\nDEFINITIONS IN RHYME\nMost things we should not\nEXACERBATE;\nMeaning\u2014make more violent;\nirritate.\nKUDOS (pronounced coo\u2019-dose)\nis just another name\nFor something that most people\nlike: praise, glory, renown,\nfame.\nReviewing the global results of\npast and current human activi\nties, it would seem that All Fools\nDay should be given worldwide\nobservance.\nRecords show that the most\ndangerous occupation is farming.\nThe most common accident is that\nof falling off some vehicle or\npiece of farm equipment. Watch\nyourself, Mr. Agriculturist!\n\u201cShe was a phantom of delight\nWhen first she gleamed upon my\nsight.\"\nBut I've changed my mind ana\nscarcely missed her\nSince 1 met her gorgeous, younger\nsister.\nThe automobile has been called\n\"the most .dangerous instrument\nin. public usage.\" All that it re\nquires to- make it completely safe\nis sensible, lawful driving.\nIt appears that the weather\nhasn't changed much since Bill\nShakespeare spoke of \"the un\ncertain glory of an April day. \u20194\nWhile anxious to give our new\nSpring outfit a public showing,\nwe keep the galoshes and storm\ncoat handy, just in case.\nA magazine article recently\nshowed that \"Spring fever\u201d is\nreal and can be. dangerous. Our\nphysical condition changes with\nseason variation. At such times\none should get sufficient rest and\nregular meals to avoid fatigue\nand nervousness\u2014which are \"ac\ncident breeders.\u201d\ni t\n(Released by The Bell Syndicate Ine.>\nRED CROSS ASKS\nBLOOD DONATIONS\nAll who are willing to donate\nblood are asked to notify Mrs.\nRobert Mitchell, chairman of the\nlocal committee, at the Y.W.C.A.\nthis week; the dates are the 19th\nand 20th, next Tuesday and Wed\nnesday, at the Y.W.C.A. The re\nsponse was very good in April\n1948 and it is the hope of the lo\ncal Red Cross chapter that it\nwill be even better this year. The\nblood goes into a blood bank and\nnone is sold; it is all given gratis\nto those who need transfusions.","height":"19437","width":"12927"}}
